I've created an workspace using Angular 9.0.7:

`ng new MyWorkspace --create-application=false`

In the workspace I created an application:

`ng g application MyApplication`

and a library:

`ng g library MyLibrary`

So at this point both the application and the library are in the same workspace and using the same version of angular/typescript.

I tried to override a getter on both sides, with different results:

```
export class AppComponentBase {
  public get name(): string {
    return 'My';
  }
}
export class AppComponent extends AppComponentBase {

  public get name(): string {
    return super.name + 'Application';
  }
}
```

this compiles without a problem. but this:

```
export class MyLibraryComponentBase  {
  public get name(): string {
    return 'My';
  }
}

export class MyLibraryComponent extends MyLibraryComponentBase {

  public get name(): string {
    return super.name + 'Application';
  }
}
```

does not compile. I get TS2340: Only public and protected methods of the base class are accessible via the 'super' keyword.

I'm using the exact same sintaxe and semantics, all things equal, can't quite figure out why the app compiles ok but the library does not.

Here's a repository with a working example:

https://github.com/brunosantosrhsenso/TS2340

Feature Description

Any way to provide time zone which the date picker will use under the hood. Right now it uses system time zone.

Use Case

I am working on a product which uses time zones to set the discount coupons expiry. I would like to use the store time zone rather system time zone when user is creating a discount and setting its start/end date/time. I have also tried using "Custom Adapter" with my own parser function. The problem with that approach is it only triggers that parser function when date is manually input rather than selected from date picker drop down.  

My implementation

`
export class CustomDateAdapter extends MomentDateAdapter   {


	private _generalSettings$: Observable<IGeneralSettings> = this._generalSettingsStore.select(generalSettingsSelectors.selectGs);
	private _gsSubscription: Subscription;
	private _timeZone: string;

	constructor(
		@Optional() @Inject(MAT_DATE_LOCALE) dateLocale: string,
		private _generalSettingsStore: Store<GeneralSettingsState>,
		) {
		super(dateLocale);
		this._getGS();
	}

	parse(value: any, parseFormat: string | string[]): Moment | null {
		console.log(value);
		if (value && typeof value === 'string') {
			return moment(value).utc().utcOffset(this._timeZone);
			// return moment.utc(value, parseFormat, this.locale, true);
		}
		return value ? moment(value).utc().utcOffset(this._timeZone) : null;
	}


	private _getGS(): void {
		this._gsSubscription = this._generalSettings$.subscribe((res: IGeneralSettings) => {
			// this.logService.debug('gs response ==>', res);
			if (res) {
				this._timeZone = _getOffset(res.timeZone);
			}
		});
	}`

In my module 

`
providers: [
